                <p>
                    <app loc="1"><lem resp="#cdl2000">hὀυμόλ<unclear>π</unclear><supplied reason="lost">ō</supplied></lem>
                        <rdg resp="#SECir"><persName type="attested" key="http://clas-lgpn2.classics.ox.ac.uk/cgi-bin/lgpn_search.cgi?id=V1-65836"><name>hο<unclear>ρ</unclear>μογ<supplied reason="lost">ένεος</supplied></name></persName></rdg>
                    </app>
                </p>
            </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="fr">
            <p><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>os fils d'Eumolpos <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>.</p>
            </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="en">
            <p><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>os son of Eumolpos <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>.</p>
            </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="it">
            <p><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>os figlio di Eumolpos <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>.</p>
         </div><div type="commentary">
                
                <p>Pugliese thought this might be a fragment referred to by <bibl><ptr target="#ferri1923"/>, p. 9 and n. <citedRange>2</citedRange></bibl>,
                    which we suspect now to be <ref type="inscription" source="#IGCyr2">IGCyr118900</ref>. So Pugliese's hypothesis should be dropped.</p>
	<p/>
            </div></body>
